sim@mppm.som.yale.edu (Benjamin Sim) writes:
> nils@cs.dartmouth.edu (Nils Nieuwejaar) says:
> 
> >> Don't forget that more development hours and resources have gone   
> >> into the Windows 95 project than for any other operating system in   
> >> history.   
> >
> >You should really read "The Mythical Man-Month".
> 
> I've read Brooks' "The Mythical Man-Month." What's your point?

No matter how many people and how much money you throw at a bad
product, it is still a bad product.  If you have a product that is
running far behind schedule, the last thing you want to do is add more
people to the team.

> Have you ever heard of complementary products? Win95 is focused on a
> different segment of users than NT or OS/2. Win95 will be extremely 
> successful when it is introduced to the marketplace. I am using Win95
> as I write this and I am quite bullish about Microsoft's success. It's
> pretty much a religious issue with most of the OS/2 advocates. I'm not
> aligning myself with anyone since I use many operating systems. 

As do I.  The point is, Win95 is an infertile, bastard stepchild: it
has dubious parentage, and will bear no offspring.  Gates has said
that all future MS operating systems will be based on NT.  That means
that Win95 will be a 1.0 operating system, and there ain't gonna be a
2.0.

> If you decide to answer this message, try to argue from a marketing point
> of view and explain to me why OS/2 will win in the marketplace.

Why?  I've never taken that position.  I neither want nor expect OS/2
or any other operating system to 'win'.  I don't doubt that many
people will buy Win95, but there are also many people who eat twinkies
a box at a time.  That doesn't make it a rational thing to do.  The
people who are lining up to buy Win95 are the same folks we'll see
lining up for Tums.
